in love but people fall in love in pretty

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:46.279
predictable terms along the racial economy.

00:14:46.279 --> 00:14:50.560
So I'm interested in all this stuff but people
don't ever wanna talk about this shit.

00:14:50.560 --> 00:14:55.569
I mean, my MIT students, I'll be like, "Is
there any race issues at MIT?" and they're

00:14:55.569 --> 00:14:56.610
like, "None!"

00:14:56.610 --> 00:14:57.610
[Laughter]

00:14:57.610 --> 00:14:58.690
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Right?

00:14:58.690 --> 00:15:01.290
They're like, "None!" and I'm like, "Really?

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:02.290
Huh?"

00:15:02.290 --> 00:15:06.399
I was like, "There seems to be a lot of Asian
girls with white dudes."

00:15:06.399 --> 00:15:10.760
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: And suddenly it's like the thing

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:15.160
that you weren't supposed to say, you weren't
supposed to talk about this stuff and suddenly

00:15:15.160 --> 00:15:19.820
they're just, their brains are gripped by
this silence.

00:15:19.820 --> 00:15:23.550
And I think that we have a lot of resistance
to talk about things that we observe everyday

00:15:23.550 --> 00:15:29.430
and, so, I think part of the work that occurs
with Yunior's voice isn't simply because you're

00:15:29.430 --> 00:15:35.170
like looking for a nice voice so that people
will read the book, I need something heavy

00:15:35.170 --> 00:15:42.049
duty to misdirect the reader so that they
will read a book about the consequences of

00:15:42.049 --> 00:15:46.829
rape, the consequences of how we seem to fall
in love in ways that Adolf Hitler would be

00:15:46.829 --> 00:15:54.579
pleased and that also on top of that, that
like a lot of us are haunted, deeply haunted

00:15:54.579 --> 00:15:59.889
by all sorts of both family, personal and
often national histories which we don't even

00:15:59.889 --> 00:16:05.740
recognize and a lot of stuff people ain't,
you bring this shit up, I talk to my students

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:09.410
about it and that's the thing in class my
students can't wait to get off.

00:16:09.410 --> 00:16:14.310
They're just like, "Yo, don't talk to me about
how everybody I date is lighter skinned than

00:16:14.310 --> 00:16:15.310
me.

00:16:15.310 --> 00:16:18.170
I wanna do it; I don't wanna talk about it."

00:16:18.170 --> 00:16:21.389
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: "Don't talk about how I, we

00:16:21.389 --> 00:16:23.930
all exoticize Asian women in a certain way.

00:16:23.930 --> 00:16:26.990
We just wanna do it but don't bring it up."

00:16:26.990 --> 00:16:29.660
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: And I think part of what happens

00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:33.009
when you create these sort of books where
you're trying to wrestle with these issues

00:16:33.009 --> 00:16:36.369
is that you need this sort of, what we call,
ledger domain, you need this kind of sleight

00:16:36.369 --> 00:16:40.859
of hand so that people are lured into the
conversation without them even knowing they're

00:16:40.859 --> 00:16:41.859
in there.

00:16:41.859 --> 00:16:47.040
And that's the plan, it never works, I'm not
kidding, it never works.

00:16:47.040 --> 00:16:49.809
It's a gesture towards a strategy.

00:16:49.809 --> 00:16:54.429
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: You know, it strikes me that
in a sense that you're a horror fiction writer

00:16:54.429 --> 00:16:58.209
because you're writing about the things that
we're scared to even know.

00:16:58.209 --> 00:17:00.190
It's very crafty in that sense.

00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:01.290
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: No question.

00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:05.480
And how often, I mean first it's a nice comparison,
I'm like-

00:17:05.480 --> 00:17:09.100
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: But how accurate it is I don't

00:17:09.100 --> 00:17:10.100
know.

00:17:10.100 --> 00:17:13.709
But sort of that's kind of a, a kind of punning
into meaning.

00:17:13.709 --> 00:17:17.819
Part of what we all do as artists, I mean,
the reason, guys we're in the middle of an

00:17:17.819 --> 00:17:26.639
election campaign, you all notice that neither
of our possible oppressors-in-chief

00:17:26.639 --> 00:17:29.380
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: that neither of them have mentioned

00:17:29.380 --> 00:17:32.770
an artist?

00:17:32.770 --> 00:17:34.429
You can go through a whole campaign- say?

00:17:34.429 --> 00:17:36.450
&gt;&gt;audience member: [inaudible]
[Laughter]

00:17:36.450 --> 00:17:37.970
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Yeah.

00:17:37.970 --> 00:17:38.980
Right, right.

00:17:38.980 --> 00:17:42.590
If that was Clint Eastwood that was as close
as we come to discussing art.

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:43.590
[Laughter]

00:17:43.590 --> 00:17:45.710
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: And we're back in the horror
genre.

00:17:45.710 --> 00:17:46.710
[Laughter]

00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:47.710
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Yeah I know!

00:17:47.710 --> 00:17:49.790
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: That was like, I don't know

00:17:49.790 --> 00:17:52.890
about you but I literally had one of those
weird moments where I was watching that and

00:17:52.890 --> 00:17:56.500
I was like, "Did I start smoking crack and
never tell myself?"

00:17:56.500 --> 00:17:58.830
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Cause you're like, "What the

00:17:58.830 --> 00:17:59.830
hell?"

00:17:59.830 --> 00:18:00.830
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: So-

00:18:00.830 --> 00:18:02.620
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: It was a media drum moment.

00:18:02.620 --> 00:18:04.899
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: My God.

00:18:04.899 --> 00:18:05.899
My God.

00:18:05.899 --> 00:18:06.899
My God.

00:18:06.899 --> 00:18:10.740
But, so, you know, part of the reason this
is always happening is because in our culture,

00:18:10.740 --> 00:18:18.840
the thing with artists is that artists are
just fundamentally attracted to the things

00:18:18.840 --> 00:18:21.050
that no one is trying to deal with.

00:18:21.050 --> 00:18:23.850
I mean, that's what art's nature is.

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:28.600
It immediately goes for a silence, you know,
immediately goes for an absence.

00:18:28.600 --> 00:18:33.059
So it's not a bad thing to do it just means
you have to have a certain constitution for

00:18:33.059 --> 00:18:38.919
it, you know, and it's, you know, like you
said, it's a bit of a horror story for both

00:18:38.919 --> 00:18:44.010
the artist and for the people because it's
not as if the average artist gets any pleasure

00:18:44.010 --> 00:18:47.360
at bringing stuff up that other people resist.

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:54.799
I mean, for real, rare is the artist who goes
to bed thinking, "Aha, I have been transgressive.

00:18:54.799 --> 00:18:55.799
I feel great."

00:18:55.799 --> 00:18:58.720
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Usually it costs, you know,

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:02.370
it's not just self validation, it usually
costs an artist just as much to break these

00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:05.850
kind of force fields but I think those of
us who are drawn to be an artist, we know

00:19:05.850 --> 00:19:10.730
this is important, we know that we're in service
of a larger cause, so, you do it.

00:19:10.730 --> 00:19:19.580
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: When you're sitting down to,
your stories have so much insight and it's

00:19:19.580 --> 00:19:27.389
a really interesting insight into the way
that men and women talk to one another because

00:19:27.389 --> 00:19:32.289
it's influenced by absence.

00:19:32.289 --> 00:19:38.140
What we see is somebody who is abs-, you give
us somebody who is absolutely clueless in

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:45.920
many ways as to what his, what effects his
actions are going to have.

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:50.360
And, after awhile, at first you're just going,
"Oh, this is pretty funny" and then after

00:19:50.360 --> 00:19:52.490
awhile you're just thinking, "Oh, wait.

00:19:52.490 --> 00:19:53.490
Oh wait."

00:19:53.490 --> 00:19:55.519
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Yeah, no, it's true.

00:19:55.519 --> 00:19:59.429
I mean, I think that privilege requires an
operational cluelessness.

00:19:59.429 --> 00:20:02.279
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: You know, I think it's no accident

00:20:02.279 --> 00:20:08.080
that Yunior is completely blithely unaware
of what his masculinity in his relationships

00:20:08.080 --> 00:20:09.389
to women does.

00:20:09.389 --> 00:20:16.259
You know, I mean, I think it's, in fact, in
many ways is part of his legacy.

00:20:16.259 --> 00:20:24.730
I think, again, it's one of those things where
Yunior's cluelessness is what always, the

00:20:24.730 --> 00:20:32.570
consequences of operating in a world where
you have privilege is you quickly begin to

00:20:32.570 --> 00:20:39.139
realize that the energy it takes for you not
to notice what you're doing begins to slowly

00:20:39.139 --> 00:20:40.380
eat at you.

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:45.289
You know, and I think that, you know, it takes,
I'm telling you it takes a lot of effort to

00:20:45.289 --> 00:20:52.919
sit around and pretend that you're not harming
anyone, to pretend that you're not predatory.

00:20:52.919 --> 00:20:58.559
I mean, no one likes to think of ourselves
as predatory but the nature of privilege is

00:20:58.559 --> 00:21:04.240
that you're predatory and I think that if
you have any kind of a soul or any kind of

00:21:04.240 --> 00:21:09.730
compassionate soul it creates all this kind
of contradictions in you, it begins to eat

00:21:09.730 --> 00:21:10.730
at you.

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:14.550
And I always think like, "God, when I grow
up" when I was growing up most of what I was

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:20.560
learning as a young man in a super masculine
culture, I came from a military parent, my

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:24.350
little brother is a combat veteran, marine
combat veteran, my sister was married into

00:21:24.350 --> 00:21:28.769
the army, my two nephews served in Iraq.

00:21:28.769 --> 00:21:31.480
My family was like seriously military family.

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:36.360
What I noticed is a lot of this shit that
we were learning as boys, as men, was how

00:21:36.360 --> 00:21:38.500
to manage our masculinity.

00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:47.230
Like what we would do to take the bite off
of that slowly devouring recognition and it

00:21:47.230 --> 00:21:49.690
wears you out.

00:21:49.690 --> 00:21:55.529
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: I'd like to invite the audience
to ask some questions.

00:21:55.529 --> 00:21:57.950
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: before you and I spend the

00:21:57.950 --> 00:22:00.070
next three hours up here dweeby nerding.

00:22:00.070 --> 00:22:01.070
[Laughter]

00:22:01.070 --> 00:22:02.570
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Well we're gonna fuckin' do
the worm on you guys.

00:22:02.570 --> 00:22:03.570
[Laughter]

00:22:03.570 --> 00:22:05.659
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: There's a gentleman in a green
shirt right there.

00:22:05.659 --> 00:22:07.950
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: That's you, sir.

00:22:07.950 --> 00:22:09.779
&gt;&gt;male #1: Oh, hi.

00:22:09.779 --> 00:22:13.320
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Oh, that's what you were doing.

00:22:13.320 --> 00:22:15.590
You're so good, bro.

00:22:15.590 --> 00:22:18.990
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: They got you-

00:22:18.990 --> 00:22:22.389
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: Oh, here we go.

00:22:22.389 --> 00:22:27.880
&gt;&gt;male #1: So I am a Boricua from Newark New
Jersey, Boricua Puerto Rican for anybody who

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:28.880
doesn't-

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:29.880
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Where North New Jersey?

00:22:29.880 --> 00:22:30.880
&gt;&gt;male #1: Newark New Jersey.

00:22:30.880 --> 00:22:31.880
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Oh, Newark.

00:22:31.880 --> 00:22:32.880
&gt;&gt;male #1: Yeah, yeah.

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:33.880
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: I spend a lot of time in Newark.

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:36.470
&gt;&gt;male #1: Yeah, my parents went to Rutgers
where you were an undergrad, I just graduated

00:22:36.470 --> 00:22:41.330
from Cornell where you got your Master's of
Fine Arts; I read your Wikipedia page, of

00:22:41.330 --> 00:22:42.330
course.

00:22:42.330 --> 00:22:43.330
[Laughter]

00:22:43.330 --> 00:22:44.330
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Damn you.

00:22:44.330 --> 00:22:48.531
&gt;&gt;male #1: Yeah and I just wanted to know
how much, you know, I'm a big fan of your

00:22:48.531 --> 00:22:49.531
writing.

00:22:49.531 --> 00:22:52.880
Last time when I was an intern at the Hispanic
Googler's Network, I started a book group

00:22:52.880 --> 00:22:56.970
and the book we read was "The Brief Wondrous
Life of Oscar Wao" and I was wondering how

00:22:56.970 --> 00:23:02.380
much of your, how much of your writing is
giving insight to those that don't know what

00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:05.220
it's like to grow up as an urban Latino youth?

00:23:05.220 --> 00:23:12.679
And how much of it is, you know, writing for
the Latino population and being that, being

00:23:12.679 --> 00:23:17.820
that, you know, that author that everyone
knows as standing up as an example and a model

00:23:17.820 --> 00:23:20.390
for other aspiring Latino writers?

00:23:20.390 --> 00:23:24.120
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Yeah, that's a wonderful question.

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:31.380
You know, I think part of what, what one begins
to understand when one, especially a reader,

00:23:31.380 --> 00:23:39.419
is that most of us are not exposed to a culture
where our experiences are narrativized.

00:23:39.419 --> 00:23:45.200
Where, in other words, we're mysteries unto
ourselves especially if you come from a background

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:47.500
like say an immigrant background or a Latino
background.

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:51.929
Often enough we don't really have any language
to explain who the hell we are.

00:23:51.929 --> 00:23:55.910
We don't have like 200 narratives that explain
how we get here.

00:23:55.910 --> 00:23:56.910
You know what I mean?

00:23:56.910 --> 00:24:02.630
And I think that often I am not writing so
that, for example, other people understand

00:24:02.630 --> 00:24:08.570
what this experience is, I'm writing so that
I understand what this experience is.

00:24:08.570 --> 00:24:14.120
And in that way it sort of opens up by being
incredibly particular, you know, creating

00:24:14.120 --> 00:24:20.419
a space of deliberation for someone like me,
it opens up that universal, sort of, door

00:24:20.419 --> 00:24:25.250
where anyone who's interested in this experience
can sort of connect to it.

00:24:25.250 --> 00:24:29.690
I mean, again, I remember when I first read
a book by someone of African descent.

00:24:29.690 --> 00:24:35.190
I mean, we live in a country where you can
actually say this, I remember my first book

00:24:35.190 --> 00:24:36.559
about the African Diaspora.

00:24:36.559 --> 00:24:39.289
I'm from the African Diaspora.

00:24:39.289 --> 00:24:43.559
It wasn't until I read this book that I suddenly
began to see and understand myself in a totally

00:24:43.559 --> 00:24:49.380
different way because many of us, again, we
live in a culture where we are in a culture

00:24:49.380 --> 00:24:50.440
and we are ghosts.

00:24:50.440 --> 00:24:55.620
There is nothing in that culture that helps
us understand ourselves.

00:24:55.620 --> 00:24:59.269
There's nothing on TV, there's nothing in
books, there's nothing in the larger sort

00:24:59.269 --> 00:25:02.860
of universe that gives us any insight into
our own experience.

00:25:02.860 --> 00:25:07.799
So I guess that's my approach, my approach
is that usually I'm writing to kind of explain

00:25:07.799 --> 00:25:14.899
this experience to myself through my characters
but that guarantees that anyone who's interested

00:25:14.899 --> 00:25:20.130
and who enjoys it will also join me on the
same exploration.

00:25:20.130 --> 00:25:25.509
As far as the last part of it, you know, again
it's you're an artist and you know that you're

00:25:25.509 --> 00:25:30.830
coming out of a community, I'm coming out
of a Dominican, African Diasporic, Caribbean,

00:25:30.830 --> 00:25:37.240
military, Jersey and a million other spaces
background, you know, nerd, whatever.

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:50.250
I guess, I'm aware that as a writer, as an
artist my presence is really just what I would

00:25:50.250 --> 00:25:53.160
call a marker of absence.

00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:58.380
The fact that I'm a Dominican writer just
speaks to how many thousands of Dominican

00:25:58.380 --> 00:26:01.260
writers we don't have and need.

00:26:01.260 --> 00:26:06.379
The fact that I'm like a Caribbean writer
explains, for me, it's more I'm standing in

00:26:06.379 --> 00:26:08.980
for how many more stories we need.

00:26:08.980 --> 00:26:14.769
I don't think I represent anyone but I think
I a marker of a great unhappy absence.

00:26:14.769 --> 00:26:18.509
So, there's other hands, yeah.

00:26:18.509 --> 00:26:20.620
&gt;&gt;female #1: I don't think this is working.

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:21.809
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: It is.

00:26:21.809 --> 00:26:28.500
&gt;&gt;female #1: Okay, so you mentioned, you said
that you think of privilege as predatory and

00:26:28.500 --> 00:26:33.409
that it eats away and you're using masculinity
as an example, do you see, do you apply that

00:26:33.409 --> 00:26:38.659
to something like white privilege as opp-,
which I never thought of as eating away at

00:26:38.659 --> 00:26:43.560
anyone since they're kind of unaware of it
and do you feel qualified to write about it.

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:48.100
Obviously masculinity is something you write
about and maybe feel qualified as a man but

00:26:48.100 --> 00:26:52.789
writing about that in terms of race issues
as opposed to gender issues where you're not

00:26:52.789 --> 00:26:59.730
white, I don’t know, I just wonder how you,
is that an analogy that you can also apply

00:26:59.730 --> 00:27:01.539
to white privilege?

00:27:01.539 --> 00:27:03.240
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Without any question.

00:27:03.240 --> 00:27:09.220
I mean, I feel like we often, again, the training
we get in this country is that we rarely get

00:27:09.220 --> 00:27:11.169
a starter course on white supremacy.

00:27:11.169 --> 00:27:14.770
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: But I think it's very important

00:27:14.770 --> 00:27:18.600
for us to have a starter course on white supremacy
because we tend to think that-

00:27:18.600 --> 00:27:20.299
&gt;&gt;Rick Kleffel: It's American history 101.

00:27:20.299 --> 00:27:21.299
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: Yeah.

00:27:21.299 --> 00:27:22.840
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Junot Diaz: But we also tend to think that

00:27:22.840 --> 00:27:26.590
white supremacy is a discussion of white people.

00:27:26.590 --> 00:27:31.490
White supremacy doesn't, if you think, guys
if you really think that white people are

00:27:31.490 --> 00:27:35.149
running white supremacy, that's crazy.

00:27:35.149 --> 00:27:36.809
They can't do the work to run it.

00:27:36.809 --> 00:27:42.379
I think that the nature is that white supremacy
is in every single person in the system.

00:27:42.379 --> 00:27:47.650
So that someone like me in the Dominican Republic,
all I have to do is take you into one of our

00:27:47.650 --> 00:27:55.899
pharmacies and show you all the skin lightening
creams, show you all the horrors that people

00:27:55.899 --> 00:28:00.710
inflict on their skin to try to match a white
ideal.

00:28:00.710 --> 00:28:05.950
You don't even need white people to practice
white supremacy; in fact, it works best when

00:28:05.950 --> 00:28:08.990
there's actually not a large collective of
white folks around.

00:28:08.990 --> 00:28:14.509
I mean, I think that white supremacy is a
force, it's sort of a gravitational force,

00:28:14.509 --> 00:28:20.280
in almost all the cul- not in almost, in all
the cultures of what we call the new world.

00:28:20.280 --> 00:28:26.899
And I certainly am very much interested in
this I mean my characters are aware even within

00:28:26.899 --> 00:28:33.929
their group of how lightness as a privilege
and darkness is something to be avoided or

00:28:33.929 --> 00:28:38.720
at least to be thought of in certainly particularly
deformed ways like, you know, a certain kind

00:28:38.720 --> 00:28:43.559
of darkness in males becomes hyper sexualized
and darkness in females becomes a desirable

00:28:43.559 --> 00:28:44.559
mulata.

00:28:44.559 --> 00:28:51.200
But, again, I think that this is something
that eats at all of us because think about

00:28:51.200 --> 00:28:59.309
how white supremacy has divided folks from
a real sense of communion with each other.

00:28:59.309 --> 00:29:01.860
You know, and how it has just damaged communities.

00:29:01.860 --> 00:29:07.269
I mean, I don't know if you've seen the figures
of how many billions of dollars worldwide

00:29:07.269 --> 00:29:12.129
are being spent by people trying to burn their
skin pale.

00:29:12.129 --> 00:29:17.279
So I guess for me it's the same thing, it's
a, any kind of privilege is a predator that

00:29:17.279 --> 00:29:21.309
eats at us, you know, but I always say to
my students, I'm like, "You can take every

